---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';

const installCmd = `curl -fsSL https://download.idr.to/install.sh | bash`;

const multiDeviceExample = `# Device 1 — work laptop (host: laptop)
idr auth login
idr device register --name laptop
idr host register laptop
idr agent run

# Device 2 — M4 Mac mini at home (host: m4mini)
idr device register --name m4mini
idr host register m4mini
idr agent run

# Device 3 — Android (host: mobile1) … up to 5 devices per user
# Each machine: unique Device-ID, unique host → unique Host-Identity
# All share entity-id user@example.com`;
---

<Layout title="Get started — CLI, onboarding & protocols — idr.to" description="Install the idr CLI, onboard devices, and route HTTP, HTTPS, SSH, and Postgres over idr.to P2P tunnels.">
  <Header slot="header" />
  <Footer slot="footer" />

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Onboarding</p>
      <h1>Get started with idr.to</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Install the CLI, register on-prem devices, and connect to local services over WebRTC — without opening inbound
        firewall ports. Works on <strong>Linux, macOS, and Windows</strong> desktops; mobile agents via the
        <a href="/isv">Dart SDK</a> on <strong>Android and iOS</strong>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>1. Install the CLI</h2>
      <pre><code>{installCmd}</code></pre>
      <p>
        Or download from <a href="https://github.com/idrto/agent/releases">GitHub Releases</a>.
        Package managers: apt, dnf, winget, and Homebrew — see
        <a href="https://github.com/idrto/agent/blob/main/docs/PACKAGING.md">PACKAGING.md</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>Supported platforms</h3>
      <div class="card-grid card-grid--3">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Desktop</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Linux</strong> — x86_64, aarch64</li>
            <li><strong>macOS</strong> — Apple Silicon &amp; Intel</li>
            <li><strong>Windows</strong> — x86_64</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Full <code>idr</code> CLI, source/target/hybrid agents, local proxy.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Mobile</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Android</strong> — via Dart SDK + <code>libidr_sdk.so</code></li>
            <li><strong>iOS</strong> — via Dart SDK + static <code>libidr_sdk.a</code></li>
          </ul>
          <p>Embed the Rust agent through FFI; Flutter example included.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Browser</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Any modern browser with WebRTC</li>
            <li><a href="/isv">Browser SDK</a> for web apps</li>
          </ul>
          <p>No install — connects to on-prem target agents.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>2. Configure &amp; authenticate</h2>
      <pre><code>cp config/idr-agent.example.toml idr-agent.toml
# Edit entity_id and host

idr auth login
idr device register --name laptop</code></pre>
      <p>
        Keys and certificates live under <code>.idr/</code> automatically — no manual X.509 setup.
        For a second machine, use <code>idr device join</code> (master approves) or a join key from
        <code>idr entity create-join-key</code>.
      </p>

      <h2>3. Run the target agent (on-prem)</h2>
      <p>On the machine that hosts your workload (Mac Mini, Linux server, etc.):</p>
      <pre><code>idr device register --name office-pc   # Device-ID for this machine
idr host register laptop               # Host-Identity host~entity-id → FQHN
idr agent run</code></pre>
      <p>
        Keeps a persistent WebSocket to <code>wss://idr.to/v1/signal</code> so sources can reach you.
        Run Ollama, Postgres, sshd, nginx, or any service on localhost — the agent forwards tunneled connections.
        The <strong>entity-id</strong> is globally unique; <strong>host</strong> is unique within that entity —
        together they form the addressable <strong>Host-Identity</strong>. Each machine has a
        <strong>Device-ID</strong> (like IP in IP routing). See <a href="/addressing#multiple-devices">one user, five devices</a>.
      </p>

      <h2 id="multiple-devices">Multiple devices (same user)</h2>
      <p>
        One subscription includes up to <strong>five machines</strong>. Use the same <code>entity-id</code> on every
        device, but register a <strong>different host</strong> on each so clients know which box to reach:
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Host-Identity</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>laptop~user@example.com</code></td><td>Portable dev machine</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>m4mini~user@example.com</code></td><td>Home Ollama / edge server</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>mobile1~user@example.com</code></td><td>Android agent</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>mobile-apple~user@example.com</code></td><td>iPhone agent</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>desktop~user@example.com</code></td><td>Fixed workstation</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <pre><code>{multiDeviceExample}</code></pre>
      <p>
        Connect to a specific device by its host — e.g.
        <code>ssh user@m4mini.user-40example-2Ecom.idr</code> reaches the Mac mini, not your laptop.
      </p>

      <h2>3b. Optional — TLS certificates on the edge</h2>
      <p>
        For HTTPS relay ingress with browser-trusted certificates, run the ACME helper on the target (with
        <code>https-relay</code> deployed). Let's Encrypt issues certs to your DEF FQHN; <strong>private keys are
        written only on the target device</strong> and renewed automatically. Traffic on port 443 remains
        pass-through — idr.to servers never hold your keys. See the
        <a href="/case-study/nginx">nginx case study</a> or
        <a href="https://github.com/idrto/https-relay#acme-http-01-certificate-issuance">relay ACME docs</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Connect from a source machine</h2>
      <p>On your laptop (source or hybrid agent):</p>
      <pre><code>idr auth login
idr agent source   # optional: long-running local proxy for SSH/SOCKS</code></pre>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--alt" id="protocols">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Protocols</p>
      <h2>Routing by protocol</h2>
      <p>
        idr.to carries <strong>raw L4 bytes</strong> over WebRTC (idr-tunnel-v1). Your tools speak the same protocol
        they always do — the tunnel is transparent. Use synthetic <code>*.idr</code> hostnames or
        <code>idrto:</code> URIs; see <a href="/addressing">addressing</a>.
      </p>

      <article class="protocol card">
        <h3>SSH (port 22)</h3>
        <p><strong>Recommended:</strong> OpenSSH <code>ProxyCommand</code> — no manual local port.</p>
        <pre><code># ~/.ssh/config
Host *.idr
  ProxyCommand idr ssh-proxy %h %p
  StrictHostKeyChecking accept-new

ssh user@laptop.user-40example-2Ecom.idr</code></pre>
        <p><strong>Alternative:</strong></p>
        <pre><code>idr connect idrto:laptop~user-40example.com/ssh --local-port 2222 --duration 0
ssh -p 2222 user@127.0.0.1</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="protocol card">
        <h3>PostgreSQL (port 5432)</h3>
        <pre><code># Direct URL (synthetic hostname)
psql "postgresql://user@db.finance.user-40example-2Ecom.idr:5432/mydb"

# Or local forward
idr forward --listen 127.0.0.1:15432 --target db.finance.user-40example-2Ecom.idr:5432
psql -h 127.0.0.1 -p 15432 -U user mydb</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="protocol card">
        <h3>HTTP (port 80)</h3>
        <pre><code>idr connect idrto:api~corp.com/http --local-port 8080 --duration 0
curl http://127.0.0.1:8080/health</code></pre>
        <p>Or use synthetic hostname with port inference:</p>
        <pre><code>idr connect api.user-40corp-2Ecom.idr 80 --local-port 8080
curl http://127.0.0.1:8080/</code></pre>
      </article>

      <article class="protocol card">
        <h3>HTTPS (port 443)</h3>
        <p>TLS pass-through — idr.to does not terminate your certificates.</p>
        <pre><code>idr connect idrto:api~corp.com/443 --local-port 8443 --duration 0
curl -vk --resolve api.corp.com:443:127.0.0.1 https://api.corp.com/</code></pre>
        <p>SOCKS5 / HTTP CONNECT proxy for browser-wide routing:</p>
        <pre><code>idr http-proxy --listen 127.0.0.1:8080
curl -x http://127.0.0.1:8080 https://api.staging.user-40example-2Ecom.idr/</code></pre>
      </article>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Protocol</th><th>Service segment</th><th>Typical command</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>SSH</td><td><code>ssh</code> or <code>22</code></td><td><code>ssh user@host.entity.idr</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>PostgreSQL</td><td><code>postgres</code> or <code>5432</code></td><td><code>psql postgresql://…@host.entity.idr:5432/db</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>HTTP</td><td><code>http</code> or <code>80</code></td><td><code>idr connect … 80</code> + curl localhost</td></tr>
            <tr><td>HTTPS</td><td><code>https</code> or <code>443</code></td><td><code>idr connect …/443</code> + curl --resolve</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Debug &amp; inspect</h2>
      <pre><code>idr resolve laptop.user-40example-2Ecom.idr
idr resolve ssh://user@laptop.user-40example-2Ecom.idr:22
idr host list
idr device status</code></pre>
      <p>Full command reference: <a href="https://github.com/idrto/agent/blob/main/docs/CLI.md">CLI.md</a> on GitHub.</p>

      <div class="hero__actions" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/evaluate">Start 30-day evaluation</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/addressing">Addressing reference</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  h1 { font-size: 2.25rem; margin: 0 0 1rem; }
  h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0 1rem; }
  h3 { font-size: 1.0625rem; margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }
  .protocol { margin: 1.25rem 0; }
  .protocol p { color: var(--text-muted); margin: 0.5rem 0; }
  .card ul { color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 0.9375rem; margin: 0; padding-left: 1.1rem; }
  .card p { color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 0.875rem; margin: 0.75rem 0 0; }
  .hero__actions { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.75rem; }
</style>
